trail Describes Mississippi Experience — Wow About Us. '
(EDITOR‘S NOTE: The
following is taken from a letter written by picks Mittlelellldt, ’63, who is now a student at the Yale School of Diyinity. The letter was written
on Oct. 8.),
Last week the National Council of Churches issued an emergency call for ministers to
one down to McComb, mississippi. l was one of the three
from here who went to McComb
for a week. Bear with me for
awhile for I would like to take
the time to relate some of my
experiences.
First a little background on
' McComb. . . . McComb was
the first city to have any “northern operators" enter and try to
attempt to organize the metro
community. This initial action
was done under the auspices of
SNCC in 1361. Because of lack
of interest on the part of the
furthermore and a lack of money the project was disappointed
As soon as the furthermore
moved out of the community,
the White citizens of McComb
took the opportunity to put the
degrees “back in their places."
,There followed a prolongEd period of bookings, settings, police harassment, and the like.
It was not until a year ago that
SNCC moved back into the
community to stay no matter
what The program expanded
this summer under the direction of COFO (Conference
of generated Organizations),
which sponsored a strong Mississippi Summer Project. Then
came the fall when many of the
students working there had to
leave to return to school. Again
the reservation of the white citizens was felt. As you may have
read in the press reports
,(what ones there were), there
have been fifteen bookings,
eight earnings of homes and
churches, plus continued are
tests, settings, and police harassment since th e beginning of July, with the majority
of these occurring in September. The total metro common»
its was, cordless to say, memorabilia. The National Council of
Churches wanted white and metro ministers from the North
to go into McComb to offer
some balance of power. Hopefully some of the reservation
could be started by having
persons in the area who could,
at any time, call out of the
state and to their local newspapers listing stories on the
config'ons in McComb.
Moving on from an ”objective” account of what was
happening, I would like to
encourage some of my personal expressions about the trip.
Dave, Jim and I flow from
New York to Jackson. The airport in Jackson is outside the
city, so we climate into the
back of a licensing for the trip
into the city. No one said a
word to us the whole trip, except one southern gentleman
who asked me if it would be all
light if he looked a pipe. (My
first and last contact with the
white, realistic approach to the
white woman.) All during the
trip the three of us, were constantly watched in the side
mirrors. What amazon me was
how we were immediately tax-
 
en for “considers." I later asked
a student here from Mississippi
why this was. His answer was
that the way we dress, our
mannerisms, and, especially,
the cut of my hair gave us
away immediately.
When we arrived in J person,
the other gentleman in the him<
online had their bags _carried
by metro posters in one direction. The three of us picked up
our bags and walked in the opposite direction into the metro
community. I did not realize it
at the time, but with that action of entering the metro com—
munich I was thereby barrel
from any further possible contact with the white community
for as long as I was to be in
Mississippi. In a sense, we had
changed identifies and were
now, for all practical purposes,
black (This was less true for me
because I am a white woman.
The hierarchy of life in the
South seems to be a very fundamentalist God, the white wo<
man, the white man, the metro,
and the ”bigger lover.” Given
this hierarchy there w are
months when 1 was an asset to
the group I was with, and there
were other moments when I
was decidedly and frightenly
(sic) a death warrant.)
Once Within the metro community we went to the office of
the National Council of Churches (NCC). There we were
briefly somewhat on how to
act in event of violence or potential violence, badly enough
this session helped to calm me
somewhat. For the night before,
before going “calmly” off to
sleep, 1 had'spent some time
trying to think out how I would
act in the different situations.
In one instance I had decided
that the best manner to contract a hosting job would be
to attempt to establish some
support with the person who appeared to be the leaders This
could be done by asking if he
knew my name or where I was
from. This was precisely the
strategy described to us. It’s
odd. . . . once in a new‘framework of thinking the fears that
gathered one at the beginning
are the accepted facts of living.
The problem then is not what
the situation is, but how to best
cope with it.
 
From Jackson we went to a
small town about twenty miles
away. The car We traveler in
was a perth rent-away car,
They are fast, and air conditional. The air conditioning
helps because all traveling is
done with the windows closed,
the doors locked and the seat
belts securely happened. perth
now when meeting to the NCC
immediately respondents the
dome light with all the doors. ’
This is so that one will never
be silhouetted in the dark and
thereby be an easy target This
was a practitioners method
learned by the death of Medgar years. ‘
In Edwards we changed cars
It was disk; we had over mighty
miles to travel; We did not know
the way for sure; the man who
was funding us had been picked
up by the police on the road to
McComb just that afternoon;
and now the car was integrated.
Since white women civil rights
workers had only been allowed
into the McComb area two
days earlier, one of our. concerns was would my presence
be an visitor not? As we traveler we were followed by p0<
like in various small towns
along the way, but were never
stopped for “supposed” traffic
violations. This was an encouraging sign.
We arrived in McComb and
went immediately to the COFO
groundsr COFO has two houses
to house the workers and one
building used as an office. Now
there is a permanent staff of
eight workers from all over
the nation — Oregon to New
Yorkia‘iso there is a girl from
Germany, one fellow from Canada, and another from England.
I was very impressed with the
calm, providing atmosphere
Each person was there by
choice and that is all that is
asked. There is a job to be done
and it is carried out in a calm
and effective manner.
Every night persons take
turns standing guard. The purpose of the guard is to wars
more who are sleeping of depending danger. Earlier this
summer the Freedom House
where the workers sheet had
been bombed—no one was in—
tired, but this was due in part
to the warning system, The
 
