“Hypocrisy has been an out-heard cry on the
Grinnell campus concerning a wide variety of subjects.
I would like, however, to explore the “hypocrisy issue" in still another area — that of the Grinnell athletic world. This issue, of course, could be philosophical1y discussed as to the place of athletics at a liberal
arts institution such as Grinnell. However, I just wish
to examine the hypothesis that Grinnell purposes a
level of athletic competition which, in fact, does not
exist. Whether the level of competition which in sexuality does exist is good or evil is not my concern
here, I am merely assessing its existence.
Let me begin by hunting first the Grinnell College
Bulletin “Athletic competition is not allowed to inter—
here with the student’s primary purpose at Grinnell,
that of obtaining a good liberal arts education,” and
recently Football Coach add powers in the Bill prison column of the Des points Tribune (May 7, 1962),
“Not a one of them (Grinnell athletes) was requested,
and not a one is here on an athletic scholarship. Every
scholarship is strictly academic" It is this image of
“keeping athletics in their proper place" that I believe
Grinnell attempts to project to the public.
In reality, however, we are a school which states an
admissions man who, among other things, is assigned
to recruiting (I use the term closely) athletes The
coaches and interested officials can often be seen eating lunch with prospective GrinnelI athletes, and
counting them about campus in a way which could
be reserved for those with 800 College Board'Scores.
The effectiveness of our “recruiting" program is
estimated by the fact that although only some 50% of
the student body claim Iowa or Illinois as their home
state, 25 of 32 or 78% of the football players must do
so. Of the remaining seven, three mail from Minnesota
and one lived in Iowa when he started here as a fresh—
man, Meanwhile Carleton supposedly our chief academic final in the Midwest Conference claims only 19
of 45 from Minnesota, 8 from Illinois, 5 from Wisconsin, and in all 13 states and Canada are represented on
their roster. As a result of this program, although I
have no specific information, I question whether
scholarship or admission is granted on “strictly" academic grounds.
In addition, there exists an opportunity for the
newly arrived non-intellectual “rock" to exist and indeed often to arrive on Grinnell society. The “rock”
